04899nam a22006015i 9780674249509DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20202020mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806742495097 a10.4159/97806742495092doi  a(DE-B1597)572467  a(OCoLC)1224278177  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 7aLIT0070002bisacsh04a363.312231 aOvenden, Richard, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBurning the Books :bA History of the Deliberate Destruction of Knowledge /cRichard Ovenden. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (320 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1. Cracked Clay Under the Mounds -- t2. A Pyre of Papyrus -- t3. When Books Were Dog Cheap -- t4. An Ark to Save Learning -- t5. Spoil of the Conqueror -- t6. How to Disobey Kafka -- t7. The Twice-Burned Library -- t8. The Paper Brigade -- t9. To Be Burned Unread -- t10. Sarajevo Mon Amour -- t11. Flames of Empire -- t12. An Obsession with Archives -- t13. The Digital Deluge -- t14. Paradise Lost? -- t15. Coda: Why We Will Always Need Libraries and Archives -- tAcknowledgements -- tPicture Credits -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe director of the famed Bodleian Libraries at Oxford narrates the global history of the willful destruction—and surprising survival—of recorded knowledge over the past three millennia.Libraries and archives have been attacked since ancient times but have been especially threatened in the modern era. Today the knowledge they safeguard faces purposeful destruction and willful neglect; deprived of funding, libraries are fighting for their very existence. Burning the Books recounts the history that brought us to this point.Richard Ovenden describes the deliberate destruction of knowledge held in libraries and archives from ancient Alexandria to contemporary Sarajevo, from smashed Assyrian tablets in Iraq to the destroyed immigration documents of the UK Windrush generation. He examines both the motivations for these acts—political, religious, and cultural—and the broader themes that shape this history. He also looks at attempts to prevent and mitigate attacks on knowledge, exploring the efforts of librarians and archivists to preserve information, often risking their own lives in the process.More than simply repositories for knowledge, libraries and archives inspire and inform citizens. In preserving notions of statehood recorded in such historical documents as the Declaration of Independence, libraries support the state itself. By preserving records of citizenship and records of the rights of citizens as enshrined in legal documents such as the Magna Carta and the decisions of the US Supreme Court, they support the rule of law. In Burning the Books, Ovenden takes a polemical stance on the social and political importance of the conservation and protection of knowledge, challenging governments in particular, but also society as a whole, to improve public policy and funding for these essential institutions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aArchivesxHistory. 0aArchivesxSocial aspects. 0aBook burningxHistoryy20th century. 0aBook burningxHistoryy21st century. 0aBooksxSocial aspectsxHistory. 0aCensorshipxHistory. 0aCultural propertyxProtection. 0aInformation sciencexSociological aspects. 0aLibrariesxDestruction and pillagexHistoryy20th century. 0aLibrariesxDestruction and pillagexHistoryy21st century. 0aLibrariesxSocial aspects. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Books & Reading.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press